    en: "Constructive eviction is the legal rule that lets a tenant stop paying rent and leave when the landlord's conduct (or failure to act) makes the rental so bad that a reasonable person would not stay. No heat in winter, repeated sewage floods, toxic mold, a landlord shutting off utilities, or sustained harassment can all qualify. The tenant has to give notice and a reasonable chance to fix, actually leave within a reasonable time, and document the conditions. When the elements line up, the tenant is not liable for the remaining rent and can recover moving costs, rent differential, the security deposit, and sometimes more. The doctrine comes from common law, paired with the warranty of habitability (RPL 235-b) and several anti-harassment statutes including RPL 227-a."
